
[1]counterbalance

   COUNTERBALANCE, v.t. [counter and balance.] To weigh against; to weigh
   against with an equal weight; to act against with equal power or
   effect; to countervail A column of thirty inches of quicksilver, and a
   column of thirty-two feet of water, counterbalance the weight of a like
   column of the whole atmosphere. The pleasures of sin never
   counterbalance the pain, misery and shame which follow the commission
   of it.

   COUNTERBALANCE, n. Equal weight, power or agency acting in opposition
   to any thing.

   Money is the counterbalance of all things purchasable.
